  "_doc": "Phase-5b demo: ALU and IR — the next two CPU components reach Verilog. Click VERILOG to see how they lower:\n  • ALU (8-bit) — pure combinational. Result R is a nested-ternary chain over the 3-bit OP encoding (ADD/SUB/AND/OR/XOR/SHL/SHR/CMP). Z = (R == 0). C is the trickier flag: an extra `wire [W:0] addext = {1'b0,a} + {1'b0,b}` is declared so its top bit can be sliced as the ADD carry; SUB borrow is `(a < b)`; CMP greater is `(a > b)`. Other ops yield C = 0.\n  • IR (16-bit, 4+4+4+4) — clocked instruction register. The full latched word lives in an internal `reg [15:0]` net not tied to any canvas wire (a translator-supplied `out.nets` entry). On rising clock when LD is high, the reg captures INSTR. The OP / RD / RS1 / RS2 outputs are continuous slices of the reg.",
